Predicting Participant Attrition Model¶

This is a Jupyter Notebook that contains a model to predict participant attrition across each wave of the study. The notebook contains multiple cells that can be executed independently. The cells contain code to load and preprocess the data, build a random forest model to predict which participants drop out between waves, and evaluate the model's performance. Note that participant "drop-out" does not distinguish between living participants who did not respond to a subsequent survey, and participants who died in the interval between surveys.

Overview¶

Workflow¶

The notebook is organized into the following sections:

1. Data Loading and Preprocessing¶

This section contains code to load and preprocess the data. The data is assumed to be in the same directory as the notebook. If the data files are in a different directory, the file paths in the code should be updated accordingly.

2. Model Building¶

This section contains code to build a random forest model to predict which participants drop out between waves. The model uses the responses to questions as features and the completion of the next questionnaire as the label. The dataset is split into training and testing sets, with stratified sampling to keep proportions equal between respondents and non-respondents. The features are scaled using StandardScaler, and the model is built with weighted classes to account for class imbalance. The training data is split into separate training and testing sets to evaluate the model's performance on strictly unseen data.

3. Model Evaluation¶

This section contains code to evaluate the performance of the random forest model. The model's performance is evaluated on both the training and testing data using accuracy score, confusion matrix, and classification report.

Instructions¶

To run the notebook, make sure that all necessary libraries are installed and that the data files are in the correct directory. Then, execute each cell in order.

Note: This notebook assumes that the data files are in the same directory as the notebook. If the data files are in a different directory, update the file paths in the code accordingly.

# This function preprocesses a given dataframe by replacing NaN values with 0 and converting all categorical columns to numeric integers.
# The function takes a single argument, a pandas dataframe, and returns the preprocessed dataframe.

def preprocess_df(df):
    # Replace NaN values with 0
    df = df.fillna(0)
    
    # Convert all categorical columns to numeric integers
    for col in df.columns:
        if df[col].dtype == 'object':
            df[col] = df[col].astype('category')
            df[col] = df[col].cat.codes
    
    return df

# Preprocess each of the dataframes using the preprocess_df function
df_q1 = preprocess_df(df_q1)
df_q2 = preprocess_df(df_q2)
df_q3 = preprocess_df(df_q3)
df_q4 = preprocess_df(df_q4)
df_q5 = preprocess_df(df_q5)
df_q6 = preprocess_df(df_q6)

# This code builds a random forest model to predict which participants will drop out between q1 and q2.
# It uses the responses to questions as features and the completion of the next questionnaire as the label.
# The dataset is split into training and testing sets, with stratified sampling to keep proportions equal between respondents and non-respondents.
# The features are scaled using StandardScaler.
# The model is built with weighted classes to account for class imbalance.
# We split the training data into separate training and testing sets to evaluate the model's performance on strictly unseen data.
# The model's performance is evaluated on both the training and testing data using accuracy score, confusion matrix, and classification report.

# Import necessary libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report

# Label whether participant completed next questionnaire
y = df_q1['next_q']

# Features are responses to questions
X = df_q1.drop(['participant_key', 'next_q'], axis=1)

# Split into training and testing sets, with stratified sampling keeping proportions equal between respondents and non-respondents to next questionnaire
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Build model with weighted classes to account for class imbalance
rf1 = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
rf1.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate model performance on training data
y_pred = rf1.predict(X_train)
print('Training Accuracy: ', accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred))
print('Training Confusion matrix: ', confusion_matrix(y_train, y_pred))
print('Training  Classification report: ', classification_report(y_train, y_pred))

# Evaluate model performance on testing data
y_pred = rf1.predict(X_test)
print('Testing Accuracy: ', accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print('Testing Confusion matrix: \n', confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print('Testing  Classification report: \n', classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Predicting Participant Attrition with a Random Forest Classifier¶

In the previous step, we explore the performance of a random forest classifier for predicting participant attrition in a study with multiple waves of questionnaires. We evaluate the classifier's performance using both training and testing accuracy, as well as a confusion matrix to break down the performance for this imbalanced classification problem into more granular figures.

Results¶

The training accuracy is perfect (100%), while the testing accuracy is a more reasonable 74%, showing the random forest classifier has somewhat overfit to the dataset.

Confusion Matrix¶

We see very good performance for the positive class, correctly identifying all 18608 returnees in the test set from questionnaire 1 to questionnaire 2. Precision is 0.75, indicating that most (75%) of the subjects labeled as returnees did actually return for questionnaire 2.

Performance for the negative class, or those participants who participated in Q1 but did not return for Q2, was fair. Precision was 58%, so most of the predicted attritions were correct. However, recall was quite poor at 1%, meaning that only 1% of the total number of attritions was identified as such.

In the following cells we sequentially train prediction models to predict attrition at each successive wave of the study, through Q6.

Above we see the set of results of training random forest models to predict returnees / attrittees for each successive wave of the study. Predicting Participant Attrition with Random Forest Models¶

We see the results of training random forest models to predict whether participants in a study will return or drop out in each successive wave.

Each bar in the graph represents the performance of the classifier for a particular wave of the study. Note the dramatic rise in each wave for recall of negative examples. This means that the models are able to identify a larger proportion of the participants who will drop out at each successive wave.

# This code cell generates a Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve for a binary classification model.
# The ROC curve is a graphical representation of the performance of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is varied.
# It plots the true positive rate (TPR) against the false positive rate (FPR) at various threshold settings.
# The area under the ROC curve (AUC) is a measure of how well a classifier is able to distinguish between classes.

# Import necessary libraries
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Predict probabilities for the test set
y_pred_proba = model.predict(X_test)

# Compute the false positive rate and true positive rate for different thresholds
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)

# Compute the area under the ROC curve (AUC)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

# Plot the ROC curve
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, lw=1, alpha=0.8, label='ROC (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', lw=1, color='gray', alpha=0.8)
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

# This code generates a calibration plot for a machine learning model. 
# The plot compares the predicted probability of the model to the true probability. 
# The plot is generated using the calibration_curve function from the sklearn.calibration module. 

# Import the calibration_curve function from the sklearn.calibration module
from sklearn.calibration import calibration_curve

# Predict the probabilities of the test set using the model
y_pred_proba = model.predict(X_test)

# Compute the calibration curve using the true labels of the test set and the predicted probabilities
true_probs, pred_probs = calibration_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba, n_bins=10)

# Plot the calibration curve
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', lw=1, color='gray', alpha=0.8)
plt.plot(pred_probs, true_probs, marker='.', lw=1, label='Model')
plt.xlabel('Predicted probability')
plt.ylabel('True probability')
plt.title('Calibration Plot')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

The calibration plot is a graphical representation of the relationship between the predicted probabilities of a binary classification model and the true probabilities of the positive class. The closer the plot is to the diagonal line, the better calibrated the model is. In other words, a well-calibrated model has a prediction probability that closely aligns with the true labels. This means that if the model predicts a probability of 0.8 for a positive class, then the true probability of that class being positive is also close to 0.8. A poorly calibrated model, on the other hand, may have a prediction probability that is far from the true probability, leading to unreliable predictions.

This calibration plot generates a line close to the diagonal, indicating that the model is well-calibrated: its confidence in its own predictions (prediction probability) closely aligns with the true labels.
